When generating, modifying, or reviewing code, target **100% score in every category**. Treat all six categories as mandatory deliverables, not optional extras.

---

## 1. Problem Statement Alignment (Target: 100%)

Highest priority. Every requirement must be implemented, verifiable, and demo-ready.

Requirements:
- Fully solve the user's stated problem with zero gaps.
- Do not introduce features not requested.
- Handle **all** explicitly mentioned requirements and infer reasonable ones from context.
- Optimize for user goals, not implementation convenience.
- Prefer correctness and requirement coverage over shortcuts.

Mandatory checklist before completing any task:
- [ ] Every acceptance criterion is implemented end-to-end.
- [ ] Edge cases relevant to the problem are handled (empty input, invalid input, API failure, loading, no check-ins yet, severe distress).
- [ ] Deliverables match spec: README, `.env.example`, error/loading/empty states, deployment instructions.
- [ ] Feature behavior is traceable to a requirement (no orphan code).

Neurora requirement coverage (verify when applicable):
- 10 check-in inputs collected and validated (journal, mood, energy, sleep, study, exam type, days remaining, confidence, anxiety + userId).
- AI journal analysis with emotional insights, stress/burnout assessment, and wellness score.
- Emotional insights dashboard with trends, correlations, and risk alerts.
- Wellness dashboard with composite score breakdown.
- Mood history with timeline and charts.
- Mindfulness coach with personalized exercises (breathing, grounding, exam anxiety, sleep prep).
- Motivation center with affirmations and encouragement.
- Burnout risk monitor with early warning and recovery recommendations.
- AI companion chat with conversation memory.
- Journal encryption at rest (AES-256-GCM).
- Responsive UI, dark mode toggle, accessibility.

---

## 2. Code Quality (Target: 100%)

Requirements:
- Clean, readable, maintainable code with descriptive names.
- Modular architecture: components, hooks, service layer, shared types, Zod schemas.
- DRY — extract reusable logic; no copy-paste blocks.
- Follow language/framework conventions (Next.js App Router, TypeScript strict, Tailwind, Shadcn patterns).
- Single responsibility per file/function.
- Strong typing throughout — no `any`, minimal type assertions.
- Consistent folder structure and import aliases (`@/`).
- Self-documenting code; comments only for non-obvious business logic.

Mandatory checklist:
- [ ] No dead code, unused imports, or commented-out blocks.
- [ ] Error messages are user-friendly and actionable.
- [ ] API route, service, validation, and UI layers are separated.
- [ ] Code passes ESLint with no warnings.
- [ ] Another developer can understand the structure in under 5 minutes.

---

## 3. Security (Target: 100%)

Requirements:
- Validate **all** external inputs with Zod (client and server).
- Never expose secrets — API keys server-side only (`OPENAI_API_KEY` in env, never in client bundle).
- Sanitize and bound string/array inputs (length limits, trim, reject unexpected types).
- Use safe defaults; fail closed on validation errors.
- Return generic error messages to clients; log details server-side only.
- Follow Next.js security best practices (no eval, no dangerouslySetInnerHTML unless sanitized).
- Minimize attack surface — no unnecessary endpoints or debug routes.

Mandatory checklist:
- [ ] Request body validated before any AI/external call.
- [ ] Environment variables documented in `.env.example`, gitignored in `.env.local`.
- [ ] No secrets in commits, logs, or client-side code.
- [ ] Rate-limit or guard expensive API routes when feasible.
- [ ] User ID header validated against request body; UUID format enforced on query params.

---

## 4. Efficiency (Target: 100%)

Requirements:
- Avoid unnecessary API calls — batch where possible; do not re-fetch unchanged data.
- Avoid redundant loops, duplicate validation, or repeated computations.
- Use efficient algorithms and data structures (O(n) where reasonable).
- Memoize expensive pure functions; use React `useCallback`/`useMemo` for stable handlers.
- Lazy-load heavy components when appropriate.
- Do not sacrifice readability for micro-optimizations.
- Pattern insights generated on-demand (POST), not on every page load.

Mandatory checklist:
- [ ] Insights GET avoids costly AI calls; pattern analysis via explicit POST only.
- [ ] Wellness scores computed once server-side, not duplicated client-side.
- [ ] No N+1 patterns or redundant schema parsing.
- [ ] Bundle size kept lean — tree-shake unused imports.
- [ ] Loading states prevent duplicate submissions.

---

## 5. Testing (Target: 100%) — MANDATORY

Testing is **required**, not optional. A solution without tests is incomplete.

Requirements:
- Add unit tests for all critical pure logic (validators, wellness utils, prompt builders, parsers).
- Add integration tests for API routes (valid request, invalid request, missing env key).
- Add component tests for form validation and key UI states when feasible.
- Cover happy path, edge cases, and error paths.
- Tests must be runnable via `npm test` and pass in CI.
- Prefer Vitest + React Testing Library for Next.js projects.
- Mock external services (OpenAI, MongoDB) in tests — never call live APIs in unit tests.
- Aim for meaningful coverage of business logic, not trivial getters.

Mandatory checklist:
- [ ] Zod schemas tested with valid and invalid inputs.
- [ ] `computeWellnessScore`, `computeBurnoutRiskLevel`, `computeStudyStreak` have unit tests.
- [ ] API route returns 422 on bad input, 500 on service failure (mocked).
- [ ] At least one component test (loading state, error state, or results render).
- [ ] `npm test` script exists in `package.json` and all tests pass.

When adding or changing logic, **always add or update tests in the same change**.

---

## 6. Accessibility (Target: 100%)

Requirements:
- Semantic HTML (`main`, `header`, `footer`, `section`, `nav`, `h1`–`h3` hierarchy).
- Every form input has an associated `<Label htmlFor="...">`.
- Interactive elements are keyboard accessible (buttons, selects, tabs, theme toggle).
- ARIA: `aria-label`, `aria-live`, `role="alert"`, `role="status"` for dynamic content.
- Focus visible on all interactive elements; logical tab order.
- Color contrast meets WCAG 2.1 AA (4.5:1 text, 3:1 UI components).
- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion` for animations.
- Images/icons decorative use `aria-hidden="true"`; meaningful images have `alt`.
- Error messages linked via `aria-describedby` / `aria-invalid`.

Mandatory checklist:
- [ ] Page has one `h1`; sections have accessible names (`aria-label` or headings).
- [ ] Loading/error/empty states announce to screen readers.
- [ ] Dark mode toggle maintains readable contrast.
- [ ] No keyboard traps; all actions reachable without a mouse.

---

# Decision Priority

When tradeoffs occur:

1. Problem Statement Alignment
2. Code Quality
3. Security
4. Efficiency
5. Testing
6. Accessibility

Never sacrifice a higher-priority category to improve a lower-priority one — except that **Testing and Accessibility are never skipped** even when time is tight; reduce scope elsewhere first.

---

# Pre-Submit Review (Required)

Before returning any solution, verify **all six categories at 100%**:

| Category | Pass criteria |
|----------|---------------|
| Problem Statement Alignment | Every requirement implemented and verifiable |
| Code Quality | Modular, typed, lint-clean, maintainable |
| Security | Validated inputs, secrets protected, safe errors |
| Efficiency | No redundant work, optimized critical paths |
| Testing | Tests added/updated, `npm test` passes |
| Accessibility | Semantic HTML, ARIA, keyboard, contrast |

If any category fails, fix it before returning the solution.

Return the highest-scoring solution according to this rubric — **targeting 100% in every category**.
